The '''Walter Camp Player of the Year Award''' is given annually to the [[college football|collegiate]] [[American football]] player of the year, as decided by a group of [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|Division I FBS]] [[head coach]]es and sports information directors under the auspices of the [[Walter Camp Football Foundation]]. The award is named for [[Walter Camp]], an important and influential figure in the development of the sport. Three players have won the award twice: [[Colt McCoy]] of the University of Texas in  2008 and 2009, [[Archie Griffin]] of Ohio State in 1974 and 1975, and [[O. J. Simpson]] of USC in 1967 and 1968.

